{{Infobox person | name = Georgina Lightning | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|birth date†}} --> | birth_place = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} --> | death_place = | nationality = Canadian | other_names = | occupation = Director, screenwriter, actress | known_for = | notable_works = ''[[Older Than America (film)|Older Than America]]'' | years_active = 3 }}
'''Georgina Lightning''' is a [[First Nations]] film director, screenwriter, and actress. Born in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], she is an enrolled member of the [[Samson Cree Nation]]. She was raised off-reserve, near the [[Samson Indian Reserve No. 137|Samson]] community in Edmonton, Alberta.<ref name = "email cite">{{cite web |year = 2010 |url = http://www.miraclevision.com/miracle.vision.press/georgina-lightning-bio-info-from-her-email.pdf |title= Archived copy of correspondence written by G. Lightning. |accessdate = 2011-01-09}} pdf of email reply from Lightning regarding this Wikipedia article.</ref>
In 2007 she was featured in ''[[Filmmaker Magazine]]'' as one of 25 New Faces of Independent Film. In 2010 she was the recipient of the "White House Project- Epic-Award for Emerging Artist".<ref name="whitehouse award">{{cite web|year=2010 |url=http://thewhitehouseproject.org/newsroom/inthenews/2010/April/20100408edmonton.php |title=Edmonton Filmmaker Wins U.S. Prize at Gala |accessdate=2011-01-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717202046/http://thewhitehouseproject.org/newsroom/inthenews/2010/April/20100408edmonton.php |archivedate=2011-07-17 |df= }} Notice of Lightning's award ceremony where she received the White House Award for Emerging Artist.</ref> She co-founded Tribal Alliance Productions, partnering with executive producer Audrey Martinez, as a means to create opportunities for [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], [[First Nations]], and other [[Indigenous peoples|Indigenous]] filmmakers.<ref name="BioInfoFromVRocha">{{cite web |year=2008 |url=http://216.109.157.86/press_release/Cree%20Indian%20Director%20Georgina%20Lightning%27s%20feature%20film%20debut%20OLDER%20THAN%20AMERICA%20to%20premiere%20in%20competition%20at%20the%202008%20South%20by%20Southwest%20Film%20Festival.htm |title=Debut of "Older Than America" press release |accessdate=2010-08-22 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Press release regarding Debut of "Older than America" film.</ref>
In 2008 Lightning directed, wrote, and starred in the supernatural thriller film ''[[Older Than America (film)|Older Than America]]'', becoming the first [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|North American Indigenous Woman]] to direct a major feature film.<ref name="FirstIndianFemaleDirector">{{cite web |year=2009 |url=http://www.cowboysindians.com/western/native/2009-10/native.jsp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005033917/http://www.cowboysindians.com/western/native/2009-10/native.jsp |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-10-05 |title=Georgina Lightning: the first Native female director of a feature-length film |accessdate=2010-08-22 |df= }} Interview with Lightning.</ref> The film won several major awards at film festivals.<ref name = "email cite"/> She based the film on her father's experience with the [[Canadian Indian residential school system]] and other personal family stories.<!---Info about the film's inspiration moved to the 'production' section of the Older than America page -->
Lightning is an outspoken advocate for First Nations and Native American causes, working towards a greater appreciation and awareness of the intrinsic value of North American Indigenous cultures to not only Indigenous people themselves, but to society in general.<ref name = "LightningOnIndianUnity">{{cite web | year = 2003 |url = http://nativeunity.blogspot.com/2003_10_01_archive.html |title= Georgina Lightning Sounds Off |accessdate = 2010-08-22}} Lighting on the value of gaming revenues for Native Americans, and also on the many troubles experienced by Native Americans during the westward expansion of American society. (Referenced article at page's midpoint.)</ref> Her three children are either currently or previously working actors. They are [[Crystle Lightning]], [[Cody Lightning]], and William Lightning.
==Filmography== * Yellow Wooden Ring (1998 as Sissy Blea) * [[Pocahontas II: Journey to a New World]] (1998 as an "additional voice") * My Brother (1999 as Mother) * [[Walker, Texas Ranger]] (TV, 1998-1999, two episodes, in Way of the Warrior as Sundance, and War Cry as Ellen Crow Feather) * Backroads (2000 as Mary Lou) * Johnny Greyeyes (2000 as Georgina) * [[Christmas in the Clouds (film)|Christmas in the Clouds]] (2001 as Louise) * Cowboy Up (2001 as Brenda) * [[The West Wing]] (TV, 2001, as Maggie Morningstar Charles in the episode The Indians in the Lobby) * [[Auf Wiedersehen, Pet]] (TV, 2002, as Lainie Proudfoot in four episodes: An Inspector Calls, Another Country, A Bridge too Far, and Bridge Over Troubled Water) * [[Dreamkeeper]] (TV, 2003 as Crystal Heart, also as associate producer) * Sawtooth (2004 as Lucy, also as executive producer and producer) * Hanbleceya (2005 as co-producer) * Ghosts of the Heartland (2007 as Tani) * [[Older Than America (film)|Older Than America]] (2008 as director, writer, and as lead actress portraying the character Rain)<ref name = "FilmographyCite">{{cite web | year = 2010| url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0510022/ | title= IMDb's Georgina Lightning entry | accessdate = 2010-08-22}} The International Movie Database "Georgina Lighting article </ref> * [[Blackstone (TV series)|Blackstone]] (TV series, 2011, as Tracy Bull in the first season)
