{{Infobox Person | name = Isabel Seymour | image = Suffragette Isabel Seymour 1910.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1882 | birth_place = Middlesex | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | education = | employer = [[Women's Social and Political Union]] | occupation = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = }} '''Isabel Marion Seymour''' (born 1882) was a UK suffragette who was employed by the [[Women's Social and Political Union]]. She undertook speaking tours in Europe. She later became a [[Councillor]].
==Life== Seymour was born in 1882 in Middlesex. Her parents were Philip and Mary Seymour<ref name="Cowman2007">{{cite book|author=Krista Cowman|title=Women of the right spirit: paid organisers of the women's social and political union (WSPU) 1904-18|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8VEvAAAAYAAJ|date=15 July 2007|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-7002-0}}</ref> and she became a fluent speaker in both English and German. She was introduced to the Women's Social and Political Union by her friends [[Frederick Pethick-Lawrence, 1st Baron Pethick-Lawrence|Frederick]] and [[Emmeline Pethick Lawrence]]. She was employed by the WSPU and was involved in administering the accommodation and bail that was required by WSPU members.<ref name=ii/> She was a confident speaker in English and German and she went on a speaking tour in Germany and Russia on behalf of the WSPU. In 1909, she was honoured with an invitation to [[Eagle House (suffragette's rest)|Eagle House]] in Somerset.<ref name=ii/> This was the home of Colonel Linley and [[Emily Blathwayt]]. They supported their daughter [[Mary Blathwayt]] and the other WSPU members by providing accommodation for recovering suffragette's. In addition Emily had constructed an arboretum of trees where each new tree was planted by a suffragette. The Blathwayts would also create a plaque and photographs would be taken to record the planting. Seymour planted a holly bush on 24 October 1909.<ref name="Hammond2017">{{cite book|author=Cynthia Imogen Hammond|title="Architects, Angels, Activists and the City of Bath, 1765?965 ": Engaging with Women's Spatial Interventions in Buildings and Landscape|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FikxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT262|date=5 July 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-57612-3|pages=262–}}</ref>
She later moved to Canada for eight years but she returned to the UK where she became a county councillor for [[Hampshire]].<ref name="ii">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritageopendays.org.uk/news-desk/news/xwomen-lesser-known-suffrage-champions|title=Stepping out from the shadows: lesser-known suffrage champions {{!}} Heritage Open Days|last=Days|first=Heritage Open|website=www.heritageopendays.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>
