{{History of Morocco}}'''Rahamna''' ([[Arabic]]: الرحامنة) is an [[Arabic]]-speaking tribe of [[North African Arabs|Arab]] descent who settled north of the [[Sahara]] between the 13th and 15th centuries. In 1525, they mobilized with [[Mohammed esh-Sheikh es-Seghir|Mohammed esh-Sheikh]] to fight the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] in [[Agadir]], [[Essaouira|Mogador]], [[Safi, Morocco|Safi]] and [[El Jadida|Mazagan]]. In the second half of the 16th century, they inhabited a vast plain north of [[Marrakesh]]. They are related to the ''Yagout'' tribe, who live in the [[Western Sahara]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tribus du Maroc|url = http://tribusdumaroc.free.fr/rhamna.php|website = tribusdumaroc.free.fr|accessdate = 2015-10-08}}</ref><sup>,</sup><ref>{{Cite web|title = Rhamna maroc|url = http://rhamna.free.fr/|website = rhamna.free.fr|accessdate = 2015-10-08}}</ref>

